            h2(id='definition') 2. Definition of a Complex Number

            p To visualize these new numbers, a single line is not enough. Mathematicians added a second number axis that passes vertically through zero.

            ul
                li The horizontal axis is called the <b>real axis</b>.
                li The vertical axis is called the <b>imaginary axis</b>.

            p The plane on which complex numbers are represented is called the <b>complex plane</b>. Now, a number is represented not as a point on a line, but as a point on a plane.

            br
            br

            h4(id='algebraic_form') 2.1. Algebraic Form

            p A <b>complex number</b> is written in general form as:
            
            p(class="text-center my-4")
                | $z = x + iy$

            p Where:

            ul
                li $x$ is the <b>real part</b> (the coordinate on the horizontal axis);
                li $y$ is the <b>imaginary part</b> (the coordinate on the vertical axis).

            p It is important to note that any ordinary (real) number is a special case of a complex number where the imaginary part is zero ($y = 0$).

            br
            br

            h4(id='geometric_representation') 2.2. Geometric Representation

            p Every complex number is represented by a point on the plane. Each such point defines a <b>vector</b> directed from the origin $(0,0)$ to that point.

            p A complex number can be defined not only by the Cartesian coordinates $x$ and $y$, but also by using <b>polar coordinates</b>:

            p <b>Modulus ($r$):</b>
            p The distance from the origin to the point representing the number. The modulus is always a positive number or zero. To calculate it, we use the Pythagorean theorem:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $r = |z| = \sqrt{x^2 + y^2}$

            p <b>Argument ($\varphi$):</b>
            p The angle between the positive direction of the real axis and the vector of the number. The angle is measured counter-clockwise. We use trigonometric functions to find it:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $\cos(\varphi) = \frac{x}{r}, \quad \sin(\varphi) = \frac{y}{r}$

            #complex_number_vizualization
            p(class="text-center text-muted mt-2 mb-4")
                strong Interactive Figure 1: 
                | A draggable complex number on the complex plane
            p(class="text-muted small") This graph demonstrates how a complex number is defined by its Cartesian coordinates ($x$ and $y$) as well as its polar coordinates ($r$ and $\varphi$). You can drag the blue control point to see how these values relate to each other in real time.

            br
            br

            h2(id='operations') Operations on Complex Numbers

            p In this chapter, we will explore the <b>rules for interacting with complex numbers</b>. It is important to remember that for complex numbers, the concepts of "greater than" or "less than" are meaningless, as points on a plane cannot be arranged in a single chain like numbers on a line. However, the moduli (magnitudes) of complex numbers are standard real numbers, and therefore, they can be compared with one another.

            br
            br

            h4(id='equality') 3.1. Equality of Complex Numbers

            p Two <b>complex numbers</b> are equal if and only if their <b>real and imaginary parts</b> match:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z_1 = z_2 \iff x_1 = x_2$ and $y_1 = y_2$

            br
            br

            h4(id='addition') 3.2. Addition and Subtraction

            p The <b>algebraic form</b> of a complex number ($z = x + iy$) is convenient for addition and subtraction operations. These operations are performed component-wise:

            p <b>Addition:</b> To add two complex numbers, their real and imaginary parts are added separately:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z_1 + z_2 = (x_1 + iy_1) + (x_2 + iy_2) = (x_1 + x_2) + i(y_1 + y_2)$

            p <b>Subtraction:</b> Similarly, for subtraction, the corresponding parts are subtracted:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z_1 - z_2 = (x_1 - x_2) + i(y_1 - y_2)$

            p <b>Geometric Interpretation:</b> The addition and subtraction of complex numbers are analogous to vectors. Furthermore, the modulus of the difference $|z_1 - z_2|$ is equal to the distance between points $z_1$ and $z_2$ on the complex plane.

            br
            br

            h4(id='multiplication') 3.3. Multiplication

            p When <b>multiplying complex numbers</b>, we use the FOIL method (distributive property) as in standard algebra, keeping in mind that <b>$i^2 = -1$</b>.

            p For the general case:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z_1 \cdot z_2 = (x_1 + iy_1)(x_2 + iy_2) = x_1x_2 + ix_1y_2 + iy_1x_2 + i^2y_1y_2$

            p Replacing $i^2$ with $-1$, we get:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z_1 \cdot z_2 = (x_1x_2 - y_1y_2) + i(x_1y_2 + y_1x_2)$

            p <b>Special Case:</b> Multiplying the purely imaginary number $i$ by itself confirms the fundamental definition:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $i^2 = (0 + i)(0 + i) = 0 \cdot 0 + 0 \cdot i + i \cdot 0 + i^2 = -1$

            p <b>The Visual Meaning of Multiplying by $i$:</b>

            p Imagine the number 1 on the real axis. If we multiply it by $i$, we get $i$ — a point on the imaginary axis. Geometrically, this is a <b>90° counter-clockwise rotation</b>. If we multiply $i$ by $i$ again, we rotate the vector by another 90° and land on $-1$. Thus, <b>two 90° rotations</b> result in a <b>180° turn</b>, which explains why $i^2 = -1$.

            br
            br

            h4(id='conjugate') 3.4. Conjugate Numbers and Modulus

            p For a complex number $z = x + iy$, we introduce the concept of the <b>complex conjugate</b> $\bar{z}$, which differs only by the sign of the imaginary part:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $\bar{z} = x - iy$

            p The <b>product</b> of a complex number and its conjugate always results in a real number. This property is critically important for the <b>division operation</b>:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $(x + iy)(x - iy) = x^2 - (iy)^2 = x^2 - i^2y^2 = x^2 + y^2$

            p Note that $x^2 + y^2 = |z|^2 = r^2$.

            br
            br

            h4(id='division') 3.5. Division

            p The <b>division operation</b> $z_1/z_2$ is performed by multiplying both the numerator and the denominator by the conjugate of the denominator. This allows us to eliminate the imaginary unit from the denominator of the fraction:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $\frac{z_1}{z_2} = \frac{x_1 + iy_1}{x_2 + iy_2} \cdot \frac{x_2 - iy_2}{x_2 - iy_2} = \frac{(x_1x_2 + y_1y_2) + i(y_1x_2 - x_1y_2)}{x_2^2 + y_2^2}$

            br
            br

            h2(id='trigonometric_exponential') 4. Trigonometric and Exponential Forms

            p The <b>algebraic form</b> $z = x + iy$ is very convenient for performing addition and subtraction or for checking the equality of numbers. However, for operations such as multiplication and division, as well as for raising numbers to a power or extracting roots, other forms of notation — trigonometric and exponential — are much more practical.

            br
            br

            h4(id='trigonometric_form') 4.1. Trigonometric Form

            p From the <a href="#geometric_representation">geometric representation of a complex number</a>, we know the relationships between Cartesian and polar coordinates:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $x = r\cos\varphi, \quad y = r\sin\varphi$

            p Let us substitute these expressions into the algebraic form $z = x + iy$:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z = r\cos\varphi + ir\sin\varphi = r(\cos\varphi + i\sin\varphi)$

            p This is known as the <b>trigonometric form</b> of a complex number. It demonstrates that any complex number is uniquely defined by its <b>modulus</b> $r$ and its <b>argument</b> $\varphi$.

            br
            br

            h4(id='exponential_form') 4.2. Exponential Form and Euler's Formula

            p For real numbers, the function $e^x$ (the <b>exponential function</b>) is well known: it is always positive and possesses a remarkable property: $e^{a+b} = e^a \cdot e^b$. Mathematicians discovered an amazing way to extend this concept to complex numbers. The key result was <b>Euler's formula</b>, discovered by Leonhard Euler in the 18th century:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $e^{i\varphi} = \cos\varphi + i\sin\varphi$

            p This formula establishes a <i>deep connection</i> between the <b>exponential function</b>, <b>trigonometric functions</b>, and the imaginary unit. Using this formula, the <i>trigonometric form</i> can be easily converted into the <b>exponential form</b>:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z = r(\cos\varphi + i\sin\varphi) = re^{i\varphi}$

            p The expression $e^{i\varphi}$ represents a complex number with a modulus of 1 and an argument of $\varphi$. Let us consider some important special cases:

            ul
                li $e^{i\pi/2} = i$
                li $e^{i\pi} = -1$ — this is the famous <b>Euler's identity</b>
                li $e^{-i\pi/2} = -i$
                li $e^{i2\pi} = 1$

            p A more general relationship is $e^{i \cdot 2\pi k} = 1$ for any integer $k$. This reflects the periodicity of trigonometric functions: after making a full rotation of $2\pi$, we return to the starting point on the complex plane.

            br
            br

            h4(id='exponential_properties') 4.3. Properties of the Exponential Form

            p The symbol $e^{i\varphi}$ possesses all the familiar properties of the <b>exponential function</b>. This makes it an <i>incredibly convenient tool</i> for calculations.

            ul
                li Multiplication: $e^{i\varphi_1} \cdot e^{i\varphi_2} = e^{i(\varphi_1 + \varphi_2)}$
                li Division: $\frac{e^{i\varphi_1}}{e^{i\varphi_2}} = e^{i(\varphi_1 - \varphi_2)}$
                li Power (Exponentiation): $(e^{i\varphi})^n = e^{in\varphi}$, where $n = 0, 1, 2, \ldots$

            p Using these properties, we can easily perform operations with complex numbers in exponential form. Let two numbers be $z_1 = r_1e^{i\varphi_1}$ and $z_2 = r_2e^{i\varphi_2}$. Then:

            p Multiplication: When multiplying complex numbers, their moduli are multiplied, and their arguments are added:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z_1 \cdot z_2 = (r_1e^{i\varphi_1}) \cdot (r_2e^{i\varphi_2}) = (r_1r_2)e^{i(\varphi_1 + \varphi_2)}$

            p Division: When dividing complex numbers, their moduli are divided, and their arguments are subtracted:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $\frac{z_1}{z_2} = \frac{r_1e^{i\varphi_1}}{r_2e^{i\varphi_2}} = \left(\frac{r_1}{r_2}\right)e^{i(\varphi_1 - \varphi_2)}$

            p These rules are much simpler than the multiplication and division of polynomials in the algebraic form.

            br
            br

            h4(id='demoivre_formula') 4.4. De Moivre's Formula

            p The property of exponentiation in the <b>exponential form</b> directly leads to an important relationship known as <b>De Moivre's formula</b>. If a complex number is represented in <i>trigonometric form</i> $z = r(\cos\varphi + i\sin\varphi)$, then <i>raising it to a natural power $n$</i> results in:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z^n = [r(\cos\varphi + i\sin\varphi)]^n = r^n(\cos(n\varphi) + i\sin(n\varphi))$

            p In the exponential form, this looks even more concise:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $(re^{i\varphi})^n = r^ne^{in\varphi}$

            p <b>De Moivre's formula</b> is a <i>powerful tool</i> for calculating the <b>powers of complex numbers</b> and for deriving <b>trigonometric identities</b>.

            br
            br

            h4(id='trig_exp_connection') 4.5. The Connection Between Trigonometric Functions and the Exponential Function

            p <b>Euler's formula</b> allows us to express <b>trigonometric functions</b> in terms of the <b>exponential function</b>. This is <i>extremely useful</i> in various mathematical transformations.

            p First, let us observe what happens if we replace $\varphi$ with $-\varphi$ in <b>Euler's formula</b>. Considering that <i>cosine is an even function</i> ($\cos(-\varphi) = \cos\varphi$) and <i>sine is an odd function</i> ($\sin(-\varphi) = -\sin\varphi$), we get:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $e^{-i\varphi} = \cos(-\varphi) + i\sin(-\varphi) = \cos\varphi - i\sin\varphi$

            p Now we have a system of two equations:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $\begin{cases} e^{i\varphi} = \cos\varphi + i\sin\varphi \\ e^{-i\varphi} = \cos\varphi - i\sin\varphi \end{cases}$

            p By adding these two equations, we can express the cosine function:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $e^{i\varphi} + e^{-i\varphi} = 2\cos\varphi \Longrightarrow \cos\varphi = \frac{e^{i\varphi} + e^{-i\varphi}}{2}$

            p By subtracting the second equation from the first, we obtain the expression for the sine function:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $e^{i\varphi} - e^{-i\varphi} = 2i\sin\varphi \Longrightarrow \sin\varphi = \frac{e^{i\varphi} - e^{-i\varphi}}{2i}$

            p These relationships are called <b>Euler's formulas for sine and cosine</b>. They demonstrate a <i>deep internal unity</i> between these seemingly different functions.

            br
            br

            h2(id='extracting_roots') 5. Extracting Roots of a Complex Number

            p The <b>$n$-th root</b> of a complex number $w$ is a complex number $z$ such that, when raised to the power of $n$, it equals $w$:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z^n = w$

            p One of the most important features of complex numbers is that the operation of extracting a root of degree $n$ always results in exactly $n$ distinct solutions.

            ul
                li A square root ($\sqrt[2]{z}$) has 2 solutions.
                li A cube root ($\sqrt[3]{z}$) has 3 solutions.
                li An $n$-th degree root has $n$ solutions.

            p This occurs due to the <b>periodicity of trigonometric functions</b>. Since adding a full circle ($2\pi$, $4\pi$, etc.) to the argument does not change the number itself, dividing these different representations by $n$ leads to different results on the complex plane. To perform this operation, it is most convenient to use the exponential form of a complex number, which we introduced in the previous chapter.

            br
            br

            h4(id='root_formula') 5.1. The General Root Formula

            p Suppose we are given a number $w$ from which we want to extract the <b>$n$-th root</b>. Let us write it in exponential form:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $w = re^{i\varphi}$

            p We will also represent the sought-after number $z$ (or rather, each of its values) in exponential form:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z = \rho e^{i\theta}$

            p where $\rho$ is its modulus and $\theta$ is its argument (both currently unknown).

            p Then the equation $z^n = w$ becomes:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $(\rho e^{i\theta})^n = \rho^n e^{in\theta} = re^{i\varphi}$

            p Two complex numbers in exponential form are equal if their moduli are equal and their arguments differ by a multiple of $2\pi$ (a full rotation). This gives us two conditions:

            p For the moduli: $\rho^n = r$. Since moduli are non-negative real numbers, we get:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $\rho = \sqrt[n]{r}$

            p where $\sqrt[n]{r}$ is the standard arithmetic $n$-th root of the positive number $r$.

            p For the arguments: $n\theta = \varphi + 2\pi k$, where $k$ is any integer. From this:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $\theta_k = \frac{\varphi + 2\pi k}{n}, \quad k = 0, 1, 2, \ldots, n-1$

            p We only need to take values of $k$ from $0$ to $n-1$. If we take $k = n$, we get the argument $\frac{\varphi + 2\pi n}{n} = \frac{\varphi}{n} + 2\pi$, which corresponds to the same number as $k = 0$ (since adding a full $2\pi$ rotation does not change the position of the point on the plane). Therefore, there are exactly $n$ distinct roots.

            p Thus, all $n$-th roots of the number $w$ are calculated using the formula:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z_k = \sqrt[n]{r} \cdot e^{i\frac{\varphi + 2\pi k}{n}}, \quad k = 0, 1, 2, \ldots, n-1$

            p In trigonometric form, the same formula looks like this:
            
            p(class="text-center my-3")
                | $z_k = \sqrt[n]{r}\left(\cos\frac{\varphi + 2\pi k}{n} + i\sin\frac{\varphi + 2\pi k}{n}\right), \quad k = 0, 1, \ldots, n-1$

            br
            br

            h4(id='root_geometry') 5.2. Geometric Representation

            p The <b>geometric interpretation</b> of extracting a root is very clear. All $n$ distinct roots of the number $w$ are arranged on the complex plane in a consistent pattern:

            ul
                li They all lie on the same circle. The center of this circle is at the origin, and its radius is $\sqrt[n]{r}$ — the arithmetic $n$-th root of the modulus of the original number $w$.
                li They form the vertices of a regular $n$-gon. The arguments of the roots $\theta_k$ differ from each other by the same value, $\frac{2\pi}{n}$. This means that the points corresponding to the roots divide the circle into $n$ equal arcs. If you connect these points with line segments, you get a regular polygon.

            br
            br
            
